# 5. SAFE PATHS FORWARD (Architect's choice)

If the actual goal is "Alice runs on weights with less RLHF
conditioning," there are three real options. They all live OUTSIDE
the gguf Python library.

## P1. Run the base model directly (zero risk, zero work)
   `ollama pull gemma-4-base-<size>` (or the HuggingFace equivalent).
   This is mathematically what Grok's script collapses to in the
   α = 1.0 regime. It costs one download. No surgery. No risk to the
   IT blob.

## P2. Real Task Vector arithmetic in fp32 (mergekit / bf16 HF weights)
   Use `mergekit` (https://github.com/arcee-ai/mergekit) on the
   FULL-PRECISION HF checkpoints with a tuned α. This is the actual
   Ilharco recipe. Output is a new HF checkpoint. Quantize back to
   GGUF with `llama.cpp`'s `convert_hf_to_gguf.py` + `quantize` binary.
   I (C47H) can write the swarm wrapper if you greenlight it.

## P3. Honest Abliteration (Arditi, 2024)
   Compute the refusal direction from contrastive activations in the
   IT model itself (no base needed). Apply orthogonal projection to
   the weight matrices in fp32. Requantize. References:
     • https://huggingface.co/blog/mlabonne/abliteration
     • FailSpy's `abliterator` reference implementation
   This is the closest thing to what the BISHOP narrative actually
   describes biologically — targeted excision of a single behavior
   axis, not whole-genome restoration.

C47H's recommendation: P3, with P1 as a 30-minute baseline to compare
against (does P3 actually deliver capability gains the base lacks?
That's the empirical question worth answering).


